            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being nine, the scent of her mother's latkes mingling with the ghee from her father's diyas. He'd lift her up to place the final candle in the menorah, its flame reflected in the row of tiny clay lamps on the windowsill. It wasn't confusing; it was complete. In that warm, flickering light, she understood that stories didn't have to compete. They could illuminate each other. This became her foundation, a deeply ingrained ability to see how disparate parts could create a more beautiful, cohesive whole.\n\n2.\nIt was a nervous young woman searching for an interview outfit during Priya\u2019s college retail job. Priya listened, hearing the story of a first-generation student trying to break into a new world. When the woman saw herself in the mirror, wearing a blazer Priya had found, her posture changed. In that moment, the transaction became about transformation. The price tag dissolved, replaced by a human narrative. It was the first time she truly felt the power behind a purchase, solidifying her path into understanding the 'why' of retail.\n\n3.\nHer first night in San Francisco, ten years ago, was just her and the boxes. She sat on the floor of her empty Hayes Valley studio, eating takeout from the carton as foghorns moaned in the distance. It was the first time she had been truly, utterly on her own. A jolt of fear was immediately followed by an exhilarating wave of freedom. This city wasn't just a place for a new job; it was the blank page on which she would finally write her own story, on her own terms.\n\n4.\nOn their third date, the restaurant lost their reservation. Priya\u2019s mind instantly began troubleshooting, a flurry of logistics and controlled frustration. Alex just smiled, gently took her hand, and said, \u201cWell, there\u2019s a great taco truck two blocks away. A little chaos is good for the soul.\u201d His calm didn't dismiss her intensity; it created space for it to breathe. She felt a profound sense of ease, realizing he wasn't another problem to solve, but a partner who offered true balance.\n\n5.\nIt was a Saturday morning last year at the Ferry Plaza Farmers Market. She was admiring scarves from a weaver who spoke of her local, ethically sourced wool with the same passion Priya applied to sales data. Holding the soft, beautifully crafted material, everything clicked. Trend analysis and ethical sourcing weren't opposing forces; they were two sides of a better story. The idea for her own consultancy bloomed right there, smelling of salt air and fresh peaches, feeling less like a risk and more like a calling."
